---
layout: post
title:  "Emacs for GTD"
date:   2016-04-16 10:29:57 -0400
categories: Emacs GTD Git GitHub
---

For a while now, I have been using Emacs, org-mode, and GitHub to do GTD and plan my life. Like most GTD folks, I have tried many different applications/frameworks. As we are told the tools are less important than actually following the GTD methodology. After all you can practice GTD with a physical inbox on your desk, paper and pen. So the process and tools that I am using comes closer to the GTD core in my opinion. My inbox, next actions, etc... are all contained in one org file. From there I take advantage of TODOs and org-mode Agenda. All of my org files are tracked in Git @ GitHub. I even export my gtd.org file to html which automatically gets pulled to my own server and served up on Apache for my viewing pleasure. Of course I have added some security around viewing the file, but I can view my GTD file from any device iva the good old internets.

Pieces and Parts
* Emacs 24.5.1
* Org-Mode
* GitHub
* Apache Web Server
*

Jekyll also offers powerful support for code snippets:

{% highlight ruby %}
def print_hi(name)
  puts "Hi, #{name}"
end
print_hi('Tom')
#=> prints 'Hi, Tom' to STDOUT.
{% endhighlight %}

